-- S.Korean stocks rise as Samsung Group units rally, won firms
-- By Jungmin Jang
-- Tue Jun 03, 2014 02:10AM EDT
-- None



SEOUL, June 3 (Reuters) - South Korean shares rose on Tuesday as an initial public offering plan by Samsung Everland prompted some investors to pick up affiliates of Samsung Group, while the won <KRW=> firmed modestly on demand from exporters.

The Korea Composite Stock Price Index (KOSPI) <.KS11> closed up 0.3 percent at 2,008.56 points after falling as low as 1,990.72 earlier in the session. Samsung Everland Inc, a key holding firm within Samsung Group [SAGR.UL], said on Tuesday it is planning an IPO next year. Following the news, Samsung Electronics Co Ltd <005930.KS> and Samsung SDI Co Ltd <006400.KS> rose 1 percent and 4.3 percent, respectively.[ID:nL3N0OJ4BX] Foreign investors bought a net 26 billion won ($25.39 million) worth of KOSPI shares, extending their net buying streak to a 16th session. The won currency <KRW=KFTC> was quoted at 1,023.1 versus the dollar at the end of onshore trade, up 0.1 percent from Monday's 1,024.1.